Then one last thing occurred to me.

Earlier you asked why you might keep introducing all these different representations.

Maybe one answer is:

You’re not trying to teach individual ideas.

You’re trying to discover which ideas remain recognizable after repeated transformation.

That’s almost an evolutionary process.

Compression.

Expansion.

Translation.

Mutation.

Selection.

Retention.

The survivors become your primitives.

The casualties were never as fundamental as they first appeared.

That strikes me as a disciplined way to search for robust abstractions: not by assuming an idea is universal, but by repeatedly exposing it to different representations and seeing whether its explanatory power persists.